## Investment Methods

### Acquisition Plan
GitLab pursues [acquisitions](/handbook/acquisitions/) which will help accelerate our product roadmap. There are a few categories across the Ops Section stages which have a [higher appetite for acquisition](/handbook/acquisitions/#acquisition-target-profile). We look for one of two things:
1. Planned future category maturity increments where the jump from minimal or viable to complete or lovable would necessitate significant R&D investment and an acquisition would accelerate that maturity significantly.
1. Filling gaps in our [themes](#themes) that span our current categories.
As a result our top priorities are:

#### Roadmap Acceleration
1. Feedback Loop - In line with our theme of Smarter Feedback Loops we are also considering Tools that enable the continuous improvement of applications via efficient [feedback loops](/blog/2021/01/20/journey-to-the-outer-loop/) from production to the Plan and Create stages, including product analytics, user forums, suggestion mechanisms, and real-user monitoring. These are distinct from Marketing focused tools that are meant to provide feedback on campaigns and content.
1. Infrastructure Cost Optimization - Tools that provide insights into cost implications (especially in MR workflows), alerting and dashboarding enabling users to optimize their infrastructure utilization.
1. CI Testing - Tools that immediately increase our capability in a Verify:Pipeline Insights group category AND provide a framework for an over-time and cross-project view of testing results.
1. Build and Pipeline Optimization - Tools that enable pipeline efficiency and increase pipeline speed to save developers time. This is especially critical for All-in-one teams that support the adoption of best practices for CI and deployment in their organization, as found in a recent research study. See [Internal Link](https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/18G8lUOHpCk2cIY2HCdROn3-IWrBgZkG9etpFM9bOxrA/edit?usp=sharing). 

#### Longer horizon acquisition options
Some acquisition options in the Ops Section aren't immediate requirements for our single-devops platform. Instead they represent our vision for an expanded DevOps platform. 
1. In line with our theme of Operations as Code we are also considering tools and software that improve the ability to define platforms (including observability systems) and repeatedly deploy them alongside application code.
1. We are considering tools that enable Operations for All by helping developers quickly define and utilize complex infrastructure setups. These include internal developer platforms, service catalogs, and IaC interfaces.

